{{subject|XHTML}}

Static Method definitly can be overriden. The only constraint is that it does not suppport polymophism.

Example:
 class A  
  {
    static public void test()  
	{
	   System.out.println("Inside A");
    	}
  }
class B  extends A
{
    static public void test() 
	{
	   System.out.println("Inside B");
	}
}
public class methosover
{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        A a = new A();
        B b = new B();
	a.test();
	b.test();
    }
}
The simple answer is that static methods are associated with the class itself, not with an instance of the class, so when you call test(), which version gets called depends on what class you call it on, 
a.test(); or b.test();
Output:
Inside A
Inside B

:Static methods can be ''hidden'', not ''overridden''. --[[User:Spoon!|Spoon!]] ([[User talk:Spoon!|talk]]) 07:13, 20 December 2007 (UTC)

