Using the oval tool creates perfectly smooth oval shapes that can be used in a variety of ways to produce and build on effects within the stage. To use the oval tool, you click and drag diagonally, moving the cursor around to test out the vertical and horizontal options of the shape. Creating a perfect circle is attained by holding down the shift key while moving the cursor to the desired size. The only unique effects used with the oval tool are fill and stroke effects.
The rectangle tool automatically creates perfectly parallel rectangles using the same method as clicking and dragging cursor to desired size while having the rectangle tool selected. The shift key in this instance creates a perfect square. The same fill and stroke effects are also applied to the rectangle tool.

{{BookCat}}

The Adjust Color filter included in the Flash Filter panel loads a new set of controls for making color adjustment to Movie Clips, Button symbols, and text fields. The best way to explain these new controls is to compare them to standard Flash color settings. Some of these controls are unique and some replicate settings available in the Color Mixer panel (for primitive shapes and Drawing Objects) and/or in the Properties panel Color menu.
The controls enable various workflows for setting and adjusting color in the Flash authoring environment. In most cases, you will start with the Color Mixer panel (or Swatches panel) to choose and/or modify fill and stroke colors for initial primitive shapes or Drawing Objects. After the raw graphics are converted into reusable symbols, the Color controls available in the Property inspector and/or the Adjust Color filter can be applied to modify symbol instances without changing the original fill and stroke colors. The sliders and value fields for adjusting color with either of these options are easy to use and you will most likely achieve the result you want with just a little experimentation. However, there are important differences between the Color Properties settings and the new Adjust Color filter set- tings, and the interaction of,the different settings can become quite complex, To clarify the functions (and the advantages or limitations) of the various settings available with these two options, we have included a brief section for each.
{{BookCat}}

A '''projector''' in terms of Flash is an standalone executable file format that Flash can save a movie into in order to allow someone to view the movie without having a flash player or a Shockwave plugin previously installed.

The standalone Projector for PC comes with the normal .exe extension, while the Mac Projector published on PC comes with .hqx extension. HQX is not an executable file, it is a compressed file format (kind of like Mac's Zip file) which packs together the two file forks Mac files have: the Data fork and the Resource fork. The .hqx file will not open on a PC if you double-click on it (because it has to be decoded), and it will not work if you burn it like that on CD with PC.

{{BookCat}}

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Hinkypunk| type=Creature| features=Marsh-dweller; carries a lantern| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Prisoner of Azkaban|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]}}
== Overview ==
A '''''Hinkypunk''''' is a small, one legged creature that appears to be made out of smoke. It carries a lantern that is used to lure unsuspecting travelers into bogs.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
The term is first introduced in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Prisoner of Azkaban/Chapter 9|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]. When [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Severus Snape|Professor Snape]] substitutes for [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Remus Lupin|Professor Lupin]] in Defense Against the Dark Arts, he instructs the class to turn to the section on [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Werewolf|Werewolves]]; Hermione protests "We're due to start hinkypunks."
[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Prisoner of Azkaban/Chapter 16|Later in the year]] Professor Lupin sets up an obstacle course for the third years' final exam. One of the obstacles is to "squish their way across a patch of marsh while ignoring misleading directions from a hinkypunk."
