== Learning as an Internally Reconstructible Sequence of Stages of Competence ({{H:title|middle of 2nd paragraph on p.3|p. 3.2.mid}}) ==

Habermas’s view is that, to understand the cognitive and moral stages of development experienced by a person or a society, one must take an internal position and reconstruct the presupposed structures that people employ in their learning experiences.  An external observer can see the contents and uses of learning experienced by that person or culture, but cannot understand the experience itself. Nor can one infer the experience of individual development from an observation of higher stages of cultural cognitive and moral development.

{{BookCat}}

== Distinction between Realist and Phenomenological Approaches ({{H:title|p. 11, 2nd paragraph, middle|11.2.mid.}}) ==

In the realist perspective, objects are assumed to exist as givens, without explanation.  Goal-oriented action, and associated kinds of knowledge, build upon these givens.  The phenomenological perspective begins, rather, with communication, and treats the putatively objective world as something whose raw reality is not questioned but whose import is determined in communication.

{{BookCat}}

{{ingredient}}
[[Image:Tabasco sauce.jpg|right|thumb|A bottle of Tabasco sauce]]

'''Tabasco sauce''' is a tangy hot sauce made from tabasco [[Cookbook:Chili Pepper|chili peppers]], [[Cookbook:Vinegar|vinegar]] and [[Cookbook:Salt|salt]], then aged in wine barrels. It has been made by the McIlhenny Company of Lousiana, USA, since 1868.

Since "Tabasco" is a trademarked name, similar sauces made by other companies are known as "Louisiana hot sauce".

